    "is_good_patch": true,
    "synth_pr": "\n## Title: Fix NULL pointer dereference in UE signal handler\n\n### Summary\nThe UE process in the NAS stack had a critical bug where the signal handler `_nas_signal_handler()` would crash with a segmentation fault when receiving SIGINT or SIGTERM. This happened because:\n\n1. The global `user` pointer was never allocated but was accessed in the signal handler\n2. The `user_api_id` was declared locally in main() but accessed globally in the signal handler\n3. No NULL checks were performed before dereferencing these pointers\n\nThis caused the UE process to crash instead of exiting cleanly when terminated with Ctrl+C.\n\n### Reproduction Steps\n1. Start the OAI UE process with any configuration\n2. Send SIGINT (Ctrl+C) or SIGTERM to the process\n3. Process crashes with segmentation fault instead of exiting cleanly\n\n### Changes\n- `openair3/NAS/UE/UEprocess.c`: \n  - Moved `user_api_id` to global scope for proper signal handler access\n  - Added proper memory allocation for `user` and `user_api_id` structures\n  - Added NULL pointer checks throughout signal handler and related functions\n  - Properly link `user->user_api_id` after allocation\n  - Added cleanup code to prevent memory leaks on both normal exit and signal termination\n  - Fixed user manager thread to handle NULL user pointer safely\n\n"
}